1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:03,237
Part Three explains performance engineering for biomedical research.

2
00:00:03,237 --> 00:00:09,306
The most important message is that faster hardware does not rescue a poorly structured workflow.

3
00:00:09,306 --> 00:00:16,994
A computation that should finish in hours can extend to weeks or months when it repeatedly scans network storage,

4
00:00:16,994 --> 00:00:24,277
opens millions of small files, requests the wrong number of threads, or runs out of memory and restarts.

5
00:00:24,277 --> 00:00:28,728
We will separate CPU, GPU, RAM, disk capacity, and input-output behavior.

6
00:00:28,728 --> 00:00:36,416
We will also explain streaming versus random access, large versus small files, compression, node-local scratch, and the tools used

7
00:00:36,416 --> 00:00:38,035
to find a bottleneck.

8
00:00:38,035 --> 00:00:41,676
The goal is not maximum speed at any cost.

9
00:00:41,676 --> 00:00:45,318
The goal is predictable, fair, and scientifically correct performance.

10
00:00:45,318 --> 00:00:47,684
Performance is not a single number.

11
00:00:47,684 --> 00:00:53,994
An analysis may be limited by CPU instructions, GPU kernels, memory capacity, memory bandwidth, network transfer,

12
00:00:53,994 --> 00:00:56,755
storage throughput, storage latency, or metadata operations.

13
00:00:56,755 --> 00:01:00,698
Improving a resource that is not limiting usually changes little.

14
00:01:00,698 --> 00:01:08,191
For example, adding CPU cores to a job that waits for thousands of small files can increase contention without

15
00:01:08,191 --> 00:01:08,980
shortening runtime.

16
00:01:08,980 --> 00:01:14,107
Start by describing the data path and measuring where elapsed time is spent.

17
00:01:14,107 --> 00:01:16,867
Then change one variable at a time.

18
00:01:16,867 --> 00:01:24,360
This approach is more reliable than guessing from the reputation of a tool or copying a resource request from

19
00:01:24,360 --> 00:01:25,149
another project.

20
00:01:25,149 --> 00:01:27,989
Consider a workflow with five thousand samples.

21
00:01:27,989 --> 00:01:35,699
If a step spends one second on useful computation and twenty seconds opening, seeking, and closing small files on

22
00:01:35,699 --> 00:01:37,728
shared storage, the overhead dominates.

23
00:01:37,728 --> 00:01:45,438
Repeat that pattern across many rules and retries, and a nominally short analysis can occupy the system for weeks.

24
00:01:45,438 --> 00:01:53,148
Another common pattern is decompressing the same source repeatedly, copying entire directories for each rule, or requesting one core

25
00:01:53,148 --> 00:01:55,583
for software configured to use sixteen.

26
00:01:55,583 --> 00:02:00,453
Performance mistakes multiply by the number of samples, files, and workflow stages.

27
00:02:00,453 --> 00:02:08,163
Estimate scale before launch: number of jobs, files per job, bytes read and written, and expected runtime per unit.

28
00:02:08,163 --> 00:02:11,688
A CPU node contains cores that execute instruction streams.

29
00:02:11,688 --> 00:02:14,038
Some tools expose a threads option.

30
00:02:14,038 --> 00:02:21,481
Slurm must allocate at least that many CPUs per task, and the command must be told to use them.

31
00:02:21,481 --> 00:02:28,531
Parallel efficiency usually declines as thread count increases because threads coordinate, share memory bandwidth, and wait for input.

32
00:02:28,531 --> 00:02:34,799
Two independent samples may run faster as two smaller jobs than as one very wide job.

33
00:02:34,799 --> 00:02:39,891
Measure elapsed time and CPU utilization at several thread counts using representative data.

34
00:02:39,891 --> 00:02:47,333
Never start many background processes outside the allocation, and do not assume that a tool called multithreaded scales linearly.

35
00:02:47,333 --> 00:02:52,635
GPUs contain many execution units optimized for highly parallel numerical work.

36
00:02:52,635 --> 00:02:58,901
They can accelerate deep learning, image analysis, molecular simulation, and selected sequence-analysis tools.

37
00:02:58,901 --> 00:03:05,167
A CPU program does not become GPU-enabled merely because a GPU is allocated.

38
00:03:05,167 --> 00:03:14,326
Request the correct GPU resource, use software built for the available driver and libraries, and monitor utilization with nvidia-smi.

39
00:03:14,326 --> 00:03:22,520
Low utilization may indicate tiny batches, CPU preprocessing, slow data loading, insufficient parallelism, or frequent host-to-device transfers.

40
00:03:22,520 --> 00:03:31,678
GPUs are scarce shared resources, so release them when the GPU portion is complete rather than reserving one during

41
00:03:31,678 --> 00:03:33,124
long CPU-only stages.

42
00:03:33,124 --> 00:03:38,329
RAM holds the active working set: data structures, indices, buffers, and program state.

43
00:03:38,329 --> 00:03:43,535
If a job exceeds its Slurm memory allocation, the job may be terminated.

44
00:03:43,535 --> 00:03:49,942
If the operating system begins swapping, performance can collapse because disk is far slower than RAM.

45
00:03:49,942 --> 00:03:55,548
Requesting far more memory than needed can delay scheduling and reduce capacity for everyone.

46
00:03:55,548 --> 00:03:59,953
Use Slurm accounting to inspect maximum resident memory after representative jobs.

47
00:03:59,953 --> 00:04:05,159
Some tools scale memory with threads or input size, so record the relationship.

48
00:04:05,159 --> 00:04:11,165
A memory leak shows steadily rising use; a normal workload often rises to a plateau.

49
00:04:11,165 --> 00:04:12,976
Disk space is capacity.

50
00:04:12,976 --> 00:04:15,691
Input-output performance describes how data moves.

51
00:04:15,691 --> 00:04:21,575
Four useful dimensions are throughput, latency, input-output operations per second, and metadata rate.

52
00:04:21,575 --> 00:04:27,006
Throughput matters for large sequential reads such as scanning a compressed FASTQ.

53
00:04:27,006 --> 00:04:31,079
Latency matters when a program waits for individual operations.

54
00:04:31,079 --> 00:04:34,700
IOPS matters for many small reads and writes.

55
00:04:34,700 --> 00:04:41,941
Metadata rate matters when listing directories, checking file existence, opening files, or creating thousands of paths.

56
00:04:41,941 --> 00:04:50,088
Network storage is designed for shared durable data, but it cannot provide local-disk behavior to every job simultaneously.

57
00:04:50,088 --> 00:04:53,708
Match the access pattern to the storage tier.

58
00:04:53,708 --> 00:04:57,308
Streaming input-output reads or writes long contiguous sequences.

59
00:04:57,308 --> 00:05:02,707
This lets storage, operating-system caches, compression libraries, and network protocols work efficiently.

60
00:05:02,707 --> 00:05:09,907
Random input-output jumps among many positions or files and repeatedly pays seek, latency, and metadata costs.

61
00:05:09,907 --> 00:05:18,456
Indexed BAM and VCF access can be appropriate when querying a small genomic interval, but repeatedly issuing tiny queries

62
00:05:18,456 --> 00:05:23,405
across the entire genome can be slower than one sequential pass.

63
00:05:23,405 --> 00:05:29,704
Against network storage, avoid database-like random write patterns and large collections of temporary shards.

64
00:05:29,704 --> 00:05:36,454
Stage active files to node-local disk, process them there, and return only the required outputs.

65
00:05:36,454 --> 00:05:43,381
A directory with hundreds of thousands of files can make listing, tab completion, backups, workflow discovery,

66
00:05:43,381 --> 00:05:45,113
and deletion painfully slow.

67
00:05:45,113 --> 00:05:49,442
Small files also waste storage blocks and require metadata operations.

68
00:05:49,442 --> 00:05:54,638
Many bioinformatics tools create temporary fragments, per-read outputs, or tiny environment files.

69
00:05:54,638 --> 00:06:02,431
Prefer a reasonable directory hierarchy, one result bundle per sample or batch, and archive cold collections when appropriate.

70
00:06:02,431 --> 00:06:10,657
Do not use tar archives as a substitute for formats that need random indexed access, but do use structured

71
00:06:10,657 --> 00:06:15,419
containers or archives for collections that are transferred and consumed together.

72
00:06:15,419 --> 00:06:20,182
Clean temporary files through workflow rules instead of leaving them indefinitely.

73
00:06:20,182 --> 00:06:22,297
Biomedical data is often compressible.

74
00:06:22,297 --> 00:06:25,258
FASTQ is commonly stored as gzip-compressed FASTQ.

75
00:06:25,258 --> 00:06:28,642
VCF can use block gzip with an index.

76
00:06:28,642 --> 00:06:32,026
BAM and CRAM are compressed binary alignment formats.

77
00:06:32,026 --> 00:06:38,795
Keeping files compressed reduces bytes transferred and stored, which often saves more time than decompression costs.

78
00:06:38,795 --> 00:06:45,140
Avoid repeatedly expanding a file to network storage merely because one command expects a path.

79
00:06:45,140 --> 00:06:51,909
Many tools read compressed input directly, and Unix pipes can stream decompressed data between compatible tools.

80
00:06:51,909 --> 00:06:57,831
Confirm that the chosen compression is splittable or indexable when parallel access is required.

81
00:06:57,831 --> 00:07:03,331
Keep the original compressed source and generate only formats needed for downstream analysis.

82
00:07:03,331 --> 00:07:07,232
Node-local scratch is temporary storage attached to the compute node.

83
00:07:07,232 --> 00:07:13,083
It provides lower latency and avoids making shared storage handle every temporary read and write.

84
00:07:13,083 --> 00:07:17,765
Snakemake can expose the job temporary directory through the standard tmpdir resource.

85
00:07:17,765 --> 00:07:24,396
Shadow rules can execute in an isolated directory, with modes that link or copy the required inputs.

86
00:07:24,396 --> 00:07:31,809
For tools that perform random access or create many temporary files, use an RCC-tested pattern: copy the required inputs

87
00:07:31,809 --> 00:07:38,050
to local scratch, run the command there, validate the output, and copy only final results back.

88
00:07:38,050 --> 00:07:43,122
Scratch is temporary, so the workflow must not treat it as durable storage.

89
00:07:43,122 --> 00:07:44,842
Use Slurm accounting first.

90
00:07:44,842 --> 00:07:51,721
S acct shows job state, elapsed time, allocated CPUs, and fields such as maximum resident memory.

91
00:07:51,721 --> 00:07:55,161
S stat reports live statistics for running jobs.

92
00:07:55,161 --> 00:08:03,330
Inside an allocation, time measures elapsed and CPU time, top or h top shows processes, and tools such as

93
00:08:03,330 --> 00:08:10,210
pidstat, vmstat, iostat, or dstat can reveal CPU wait, memory pressure, and storage activity when available.

94
00:08:10,210 --> 00:08:16,230
N v i d i a s m i reports GPU utilization and memory.

95
00:08:16,230 --> 00:08:19,669
Snakemake benchmark files connect measurements to specific rules.

96
00:08:19,669 --> 00:08:27,409
Interpret metrics together: low CPU plus high I/O wait suggests storage; full memory and rising swap suggests RAM;

97
00:08:27,409 --> 00:08:32,139
low GPU utilization with busy CPUs suggests preprocessing or data loading.

98
00:08:32,139 --> 00:08:34,623
A symptom is not a diagnosis.

99
00:08:34,623 --> 00:08:41,247
Low CPU efficiency may be caused by input-output wait, serial code, thread oversubscription, or frequent synchronization.

100
00:08:41,247 --> 00:08:48,699
A job killed for memory needs either a larger allocation or a method that reduces the working set.

101
00:08:48,699 --> 00:08:54,909
A GPU at ten percent utilization may be waiting on CPU preprocessing or tiny batches.

102
00:08:54,909 --> 00:08:59,877
A workflow that pauses while discovering files may have a metadata problem.

103
00:08:59,877 --> 00:09:06,087
Build a small representative benchmark, change one factor, and compare elapsed time and resource efficiency.

104
00:09:06,087 --> 00:09:13,125
Stop when performance is adequate and fair; optimization also has engineering cost and can introduce scientific errors.

105
00:09:13,125 --> 00:09:15,412
The operating rules are straightforward.

106
00:09:15,412 --> 00:09:16,785
Measure before scaling.

107
00:09:16,785 --> 00:09:19,988
Match Slurm requests to the software configuration.

108
00:09:19,988 --> 00:09:22,733
Keep source data compressed where possible.

109
00:09:22,733 --> 00:09:24,563
Prefer sequential streaming access.

110
00:09:24,563 --> 00:09:27,765
Avoid random temporary input-output on network storage.

111
00:09:27,765 --> 00:09:32,798
Stage active files to node-local scratch through a tested Snakemake pattern.

112
00:09:32,798 --> 00:09:35,086
Reduce small-file and directory counts.

113
00:09:35,086 --> 00:09:38,746
Preserve only necessary outputs and clean temporary files.

114
00:09:38,746 --> 00:09:44,694
Use Slurm accounting, Snakemake benchmarks, and operating-system tools to identify the actual bottleneck.

115
00:09:44,694 --> 00:09:48,354
Above all, perform a pilot at realistic scale.

116
00:09:48,354 --> 00:09:57,047
An inefficient workflow multiplied across thousands of samples can turn hours into months and degrade the shared service for

117
00:09:57,047 --> 00:09:57,505
colleagues.

